ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The symptoms manifested in this outbreak and the time between the
suspected ingestion and the onset of illness are not stated in the
posting. Iron toxicity initially presents as nausea, vomiting, and
abdominal pain within 1-2 hours after the ingestion of doses of 10 to 20
mg/kg of the equivalent of elemental iron. If the toxicity is profound,
subsequent systemic effects include hypotension and shock as well as
hepatoxicity. Specific management can include limiting iron absorption by
using activated charcoal and/or by administering compounds (phosphates or
bicarbonates) that complex with iron in the gut to produce insoluble salts.
Desferroxiamine can be administered systemically to complex with iron in
appropriate circumstances.
Reference: Perrone J. Iron. In, Goldfrank's Toxicologic Emergencies,
Goldfrank LR, Flomenbaum NE, Lewin NA, et al (eds), 7th ed., McGraw-Hill,
NY, pp 548-57. - Mod.LL]
